riptiongogr00gugoog|volume=3: Galilee, pt. 2|year=1880|publisher= L'Imprimerie Nationale|location=Paris|language=French}} \n* {{cite book|title=Village Statistics of 1945: A Classification of Land and Area ownership in Palestine|url=http://www.palestineremembered.com/Articles/General-2/Story3150.html|first=S.|last=Hadawi|authorlink=Sami Hadawi|year=1970|publisher=Palestine Liberation Organization Research Center}}\n* {{cite book | last1= H\u00fctteroth |first1=Wolf-Dieter |first2=Kamal | last2=Abdulfattah | title = Historical Geography of Palestine, Transjordan and Southern Syria in the Late 16th Century |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wqULAAAAIAAJ | year = 1977 | publisher = Erlanger Geographische Arbeiten, Sonderband 5. Erlangen, Germany: Vorstand der Fr\u00e4nkischen Geographischen Gesellschaft|isbn= 3-920405-41-2}}\n* {{cite book | editor = Mills, E. | title = Census of Palestine 1931. Population of Villages, Towns and Administrative Areas |url=https://archive.org/details/CensusOfPalestine1931.PopulationOfVillagesTownsAndAdministrativeAreas | publisher = Government of Palestine | location = Jerusalem | year = 1932}} \n* {{cite book|last=Morris|first=B.|authorlink=Benny Morris|year=1987|title=The Birth of the Palestinian Refugee Problem|isbn=0-521-33028-9|publisher=Cambridge University Press|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/birthofpalestini00morr}} \n* {{cite book|last=Palmer|first=E.H.|authorlink=Edward Henry Palmer|year=1881|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp00conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Arabic and English Name Lists Collected During the Survey by Lieutenants Conder and Kitchener, R. E. Transliterated and Explained by E.H. Palmer|publisher=[[Palestine Exploration Fund|Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund]]}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Robinson|first1=E.|authorlink1=Edward Robinson (scholar)|last2=Smith|first2=E.|authorlink2=Eli Smith|year=1841|url=https://archive.org/details/biblicalresearch03robiuoft |title=Biblical Researches in Palestine, Mount Sinai and Arabia Petraea: A Journal of Travels in the year 1838| location=Boston|publisher=[[Crocker & Brewster]]|volume=3}}\n* {{cite book|last=R\u00f6hricht|first=R. |authorlink=Reinhold R\u00f6hricht|title= (RRH) Regesta regni Hierosolymitani (MXCVII-MCCXCI)|url=https://archive.org/details/regestaregnihie00rhgoog|year=1893|publisher=Libraria Academica Wageriana|location=Berlin|language=Latin}}\n* {{cite journal | last = Schumacher | first =G.| authorlink = Gottlieb Schumacher | title = Population list of the Liwa of Akka | journal = Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund | volume = 20 | pages = 169\u2013191 | url = https://archive.org/details/quarterlystateme19pale | year = 1888}}\n* {{cite book|editor=Strehlke, Ernst |title=Tabulae Ordinis Theutonici ex tabularii regii Berolinensis codice potissimum|url=https://archive.org/details/tabulaeordinist00stregoog|year=1869|publisher= Weidmanns|location=Berlin}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Tahan |first=Hagit |date= 2008-12-30 |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=990&mag_id=115 |title=Fassuta Final Report |publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel|number=121}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.palestineremembered.com/GeoPoints/Fassuta_1132/index.html Welcome To Fassuta]\n* Survey of Western Palestine, Map 4: [http://www.iaa-archives.org.il/zoom/zoom.aspx?folder_id=93&type_id=6&id=8367 IAA], [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Survey_of_Western_Palestine_1880.04.jpg Wikimedia commons]\n{{Northern District (Israel)}}\n\n[[Category:Arab localities in Israel]]\n[[Category:Arab Christian communities in Israel]]\n[[Category:Local councils in Northern District (Israel)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Israel municipality\n|name=Fassouta\n|image_skyline=PikiWiki Israel 8821 entrance to fassuta.jpg\n|image_caption=Entrance to Fassouta\n|hebname={{Hebrew|\u05e4\u05b7\u05e1\u05bc\u05d5\u05bc\u05d8\u05b8\u05d4}}\n|ISO=P\u0304ass\u00fa\u1e6da\n|arname=\u0641\u0633\u0648\u0637\u0629\n|meaning=Fassute, personal name<ref>Palmer, 1881, p. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp00conduoft#page/72/mode/1up 72]</ref>\n|coordinates = {{coord|33|02|58|N|35|18|21|E|region:IL|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|palgrid=179/272\n|founded=\n|type=lc\n|typefrom=\n|stdHeb=\n|altOffSp=\n|altUnoSp=\n|district=north\n| popyear = {{Israel populations|Year}}\n| population = {{Israel populations|Fassuta}}\n| population_footnotes={{Israel populations|reference}}\n|pushpin_map=Israel northwest#Israel\n|pushpin_mapsize=250\n|area_dunam=\n|mayor=\n}}\n\n'''Fassouta''' ({{lang-ar|\u0641\u0633\u0648\u0637\u0629}}, {{lang-he-n|\u05e4\u05b7\u05e1\u05bc\u05d5\u05bc\u05d8\u05b8\u05d4\u202c}}) is a [[local council (Israel)|local council]] on the northwestern slopes of [[Mount Meron]] in the [[Northern District (Israel)|Northern District]] of [[Israel]], south of the Lebanese border.<ref name=Elias>{{cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/1.4956915|title=Galilee Villages Launch Campaign to Attract Christian Pilgrims|author=Stern, Yoav|date=2007-04-30|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]|accessdate=2019-02-18}}</ref> In {{Israel populations|Year}} it had a population of {{Israel populations|Fassuta}}, nearly all of whom are [[Palestinian Christians|Christians]].{{Israel populations|reference}}\n\n==History==\nThere have been several archaeological excavation at Fassuta, which reveal  settlement from the [[Bronze Age#Near East timeline|Early Bronze Age]], through the  [[Ancient Near East#Iron Age|Iron Age]], [[Hellenistic period|Hellenistic]] and the [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk]] eras.<ref>Bron, 2007, [http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=513&mag_id=112 Fassuta]</ref><ref>Tahan, 2009, [http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=990&mag_id=115 Fassuta]</ref><ref>Bron,  2010, [http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1387&mag_id=117 Fassuta]</ref><ref>Abu-\u2018Uqsa, 2013, [http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=5422&mag_id=120 Fassuta, Survey]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Crusader states|Crusader era]] Fassuta was known as ''Fassove''.<ref>[https://books.google.co.il/books?id=AB_aW2OLSrQC&pg=PA11&lpg=PA11&dq=fassouta+jewish+village&source=bl&ots=lPz3llcYOB&sig=ACfU3U2InbiGmQKU1iJUL_GP-LsbgSozPQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjVw9r5v6DkAhXE1qQKHU3uC5g4ChDoATAFegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=fassouta%20jewish%20village&f=false Arabesques: A Novel], by  [[Anton Shammas]]</ref>{{cn|date=February 2020}} In 1183 it was noted that  ''[[Officers of the Kingdom of Cyprus#Chamberlain|Godfrey de Tor]]'' sold  the land of the village  to [[Joscelin III, Count of Edessa|Joscelin III]].<ref>Strehlke, 1869, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/tabulaeordinist00stregoog#page/n31/mode/1up 15]-16, No. 16; cited in R\u00f6hricht, 1893, RRH, p. [https://archive.org/stream/regestaregnihie00rhgoog#page/n171/mode/1up 125], No. 624; cited in Frankel, 1988, pp. 257, 264</ref> In 1220  Jocelyn III\u00b4s daughter [[Beatrix de Courtenay]] and her husband [[Otto von Botenlauben]], [[House of Henneberg|Count of Henneberg]],  sold  their land, including ''Fassove'', to the [[Teutonic Knights]].<ref>Strehlke, 1869, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/tabulaeordinist00stregoog#page/n59/mode/1up 43]- 44, No. 53; cited in R\u00f6hricht, 1893, RRH, p. [https://archive.org/stream/regestaregnihie00rhgoog#page/n254/mode/1up 248], No. 934; cited in Frankel, 1988, pp. 257, 264</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE0DF1339F93BA2575AC0A96E948260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=4|title=An Arab Voice in Israel|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Marzorati, Gerald|date=1988-09-11|accessdate=2008-10-25}}</ref>\n\n===Ottoman era===\nFassuta   was incorporated into the [[Ottoman Empire]] in 1517, and in the 1596 [[Defter|tax records]] it was  part of  the ''[[Nahiya]]'' of Akka of the  [[Safad Sanjak]].  It had a population of 12 [[Muslim]] households and 3 Muslim bachelors. The villagers paid a fixed tax-rate of 20%  on wheat, barley, fruit trees, and goats or beehives; a total of 1,988 [[ak\u00e7e]].<ref>H\u00fctteroth and Abdulfattah, 1977, p. 194</ref>\n\nIn 1838 ''Fesutha'' was noted as a Christian and [[Druze]] village in the ''El-Jebel'' district, west of [[Safad]].<ref>Robinson and Smith, 1841, vol 3, 2nd appendix, p. [https://archive.org/stream/biblicalresearch03robiuoft#page/133/mode/1up 133]</ref>\n\nIn 1881, the [[Palestine Exploration Fund|PEF]]'s  \"[[PEF Survey of Palestine|Survey of Western Palestine]]\" (SWP)  described  Fassuta as \"a village, built of stone, containing about 200 Christians, situated on ridge, with gardens of figs, olives, and arable land. There are two [[cistern]]s in the village, and a good spring near.\"<ref name=\"SWPI\">Conder and Kitchener, 1881, SWP I, p. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp01conduoft#page/197/mode/1up 197]</ref>\n\nA population list from about 1887 showed  ''Fassutah'' to have  about 570 inhabitants.<ref>Schumacher, 1888, p. [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme19pale#page/n216/mode/1up  191]</ref>\n\n===British Mandate era===\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 8822 the church in fassuta.jpg|thumb|right|Mar Elias Church]]\nAt the time of the [[1922 census of Palestine]] conducted by the  [[British Mandate for Palestine (legal instrument)|British Mandate]], Fassuta had a population of  459,  444 Christians and 15 Muslims,<ref>Barron, 1923, Table XI, Sub-district of Acre, p. [https://archive.org/stream/PalestineCensus1922/Palestine%20Census%20%281922%29#page/n38/mode/1up  36]</ref> where the Christians were 1 Orthodox, 18 Syrian orthodox, and 425 [[Melkite]]s.<ref>Barron, 1923, Table XVI, p.[https://archive.org/stream/PalestineCensus1922/Palestine%20Census%20%281922%29#page/n52/mode/1up 50]</ref> In  the [[1931 census of Palestine|1931 census]], the combined population of Fassuta and [[Al-Mansura, Acre|Mansura]] was 507 [[Palestinian Christians]] and 81 Muslims, living in a total of 129 houses.<ref name=\"Census1931\">Mills, 1932, p. [https://archive.org/details/CensusOfPalestine1931.PopulationOfVillagesTownsAndAdministrativeAreas  100]</ref>\n\nIn  the [[Village Statistics, 1945|1945 statistics]]  Fassuta had 1,050  inhabitants.<ref name=1945p4>Department of Statistics, 1945, p. [http://users.cecs.anu.edu.au/~bdm/yabber/census/VSpages/VS1945_p04.jpg   4]</ref><ref name=1945data/>  The combined population of Fassuta, [[Al-Mansura, Acre|Al-Mansura]]  and [[Dayr al-Qassi|Dayr al-Qasi]] was 2,300, and their  total land area was 34,011 dunums.<ref name=1945data>[http://domino.un.org/pdfs/AAC25ComTech7Add1.pdf ''Village Statistics April 1945,'' The Palestine Government] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609000000/http://domino.un.org/pdfs/AAC25ComTech7Add1.pdf |date=June 9, 2012 }}, p. 2</ref><ref name=Hadawip40>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in Hadawi, 1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20I/Acre/Page-040.jpg 40]</ref>   1,607 dunams were plantations and irrigable land, 6,475 used for cereals,<ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in  Hadawi,  1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20II/Acre/Page-080.jpg 80]</ref> while 247  dunams were built-up (urban) land.<ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in Hadawi, 1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20III/Acre/Page-130.jpg  130]</ref>\nBetween 1922 and 1947, the population of Fassuta increased by 120%.<ref>Transformation in Arab Settlement, [[Moshe Brawer]], in ''The Land that Became Israel: Studies in Historical Geography'', [[Ruth Kark]] (ed), Magnes Press, Jerusalem 1989, p.177</ref>\n===1948, and aftermath===\nAt the end of October 1948 the village was captured by the Israeli army during [[Operation Hiram]]. Most of the Muslim population fled or were expelled but many of the Christians remained. In December 1949 the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] put forward a plan to expel the remaining population of Fassuta and five other villages in order to create a 5\u201310&nbsp;km Arab-free zone along the [[Lebanon]] border. This plan was blocked by the Foreign Ministry which feared international reaction.<ref>Morris, 1987, pp. 225, 242, 251</ref> The Arab population remained under [[Martial law#Israel|Martial Law]] until 1966.\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 2005, the population of Fassuta was 2,900 residents, with an annual population growth rate of 0.9%. All of the inhabitants are [[Christians]] of the [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Melkite (Greek) Catholic Church]].<ref>[http://www.cbs.gov.il/publications16/local_authorities14_1642/pdf/844_0535.pdf \u05e4\u05e1\u05d5\u05d8\u05d4 2014]</ref> In 2000, 60.5% of Fassuta high school students passed the [[Bagrut]] matriculation exam. {{citation needed|date=November 2011}} In 2000, the mean income was [[Israeli new shekel|NIS]] 3,748, compared to a national average of NIS 6,835.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\n==Religion and culture==\nIn 2007, the Mar Elias Church in Fassuta celebrated its 100th anniversary. The church is named after [[Elijah|Elias]], the village's [[patron saint]]. A large statue of [[Elijah|Mar Elias]] stands in the central square.<ref name=\"Elias\" />\n\n==Archaeology==\nIn  1875, [[Victor Gu\u00e9rin|Guerin]]  found traces of ancient ruins: \"Numerous [[cistern]]s, a great reservoir, vestiges of many ruined houses, fine cut stones marking out floors, and a dozen of presses nearly perfect. These presses are all on the same model : worked in the rock, they consisted of two compartments, one larger, in which the grapes were placed,\nand one smaller and lower down, in which the juice was received. In the humble church of the modern hamlet I remarked a chapter imitating   [[Corinthian order|Corinthian]], and probably of [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] period. On two of its faces a cross with equal branches has been sculptured. Above the door of the main [[church (building)|church]] has been placed for a  [[Lintel (architecture)|lintel]] a fragment of [[frieze]] decorated with\nflowers and foliage elegantly executed.\"<ref name=\"GuerinG2\">Gu\u00e9rin, 1880, p. [https://archive.org/stream/descriptiongogr00gugoog#page/n83/mode/1up 67], as translated by  Conder and Kitchener, 1881, SWP I, p.  [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp01conduoft#page/222/mode/1up 222]</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n* [[Sabri Jiryis]]<ref>{{cite book| last = El-Asmar| first = Fouzi| title = To Be an Arab in Israel| publisher = Frances Pinter| date = 1975| location = London| pages= 177\u20138| isbn = 0-903804-08-5}}</ref>\n* [[Anton Shammas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sakakini.org/literature/anton.htm|title=Anton Shammas|publisher=Khalil Sakakini Cultural Center|access-date=2008-10-25|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080607141248/http://www.sakakini.org/literature/anton.htm|archive-date=2008-06-07|df=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Arab localities in Israel]]\n* [[Christianity in Israel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Abu-\u2018Uqsa |first=Hanaa |date= 2013-12-12   |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=5422&mag_id=120  |title=Fassuta, Survey Final Report |publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel|number=125}} \n* {{cite book | editor =Barron,  J. B. | title = Palestine: Report and General Abstracts of the Census of 1922 |url=https://archive.org/details/PalestineCensus1922 |publisher = Government of Palestine | year = 1923}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Bron|first=Hendrik (Enno) |date= 2007-04-22   |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=513&mag_id=112  |title=Fassuta Final  Report|publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel|number=119}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Bron|first=Hendrik (Enno) |date= 2010-05-18   |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1387&mag_id=117 |title=Fassuta Preliminary Report |publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel|number=122}} \n* {{cite book|last1=Conder|first1=C.R.|authorlink1=Claude Reignier Conder|last2=Kitchener|first2=H.H.|authorlink2=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|year=1881|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp01conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Memoirs of the Topography, Orography, Hydrography, and Archaeology|location=London|publisher=[[Palestine Exploration Fund|Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund]]|volume=1}} \n* {{cite book | last= Dauphin |first = Claudine  | title = La Palestine byzantine, Peuplement et Populations |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FC1mAAAAMAAJ |volume = III : Catalogue | series = BAR International Series 726 | year = 1998 | publisher = Archeopress | location = Oxford|language =French|isbn= 0-860549-05-4}}  (p.&nbsp;633 )\n* {{cite book|title=Village Statistics, April, 1945 |url=http://web.nli.org.il/sites/nli/Hebrew/library/Pages/BookReader.aspx?pid=856390|author=Department of Statistics|year=1945|publisher=Government of Palestine}}\n* {{cite journal | first1=Rafael | last1=Frankel | title=Topographical notes on the territory of Acre in the Crusader period | journal= [[Israel Exploration Journal]] | volume=38 | number= 4 | year=1988 | pages= 249\u2013272}}\n* {{cite book|last=Gu\u00e9rin|first=V.|authorlink=Victor Gu\u00e9rin|title=Description G\u00e9ographique Historique et Arch\u00e9ologique de la Palestine|url=https://archive.org/details/descriptiongogr00gugoog|volume=3: Galilee,  pt. 2|year=1880|publisher= L'Imprimerie Nationale|location=Paris|language=French}} \n* {{cite book|title=Village Statistics of 1945: A Classification of Land and Area ownership in Palestine|url=http://www.palestineremembered.com/Articles/General-2/Story3150.html|first=S.|last=Hadawi|authorlink=Sami Hadawi|year=1970|publisher=Palestine Liberation Organization Research Center}}\n* {{cite book | last1= H\u00fctteroth |first1=Wolf-Dieter |first2=Kamal | last2=Abdulfattah | title = Historical Geography of Palestine, Transjordan and Southern Syria in the Late 16th Century |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wqULAAAAIAAJ  | year = 1977 | publisher = Erlanger Geographische Arbeiten, Sonderband 5. Erlangen, Germany: Vorstand der Fr\u00e4nkischen Geographischen Gesellschaft|isbn= 3-920405-41-2}}\n* {{cite book | editor = Mills, E.  | title = Census of Palestine 1931. Population of Villages, Towns and Administrative Areas |url=https://archive.org/details/CensusOfPalestine1931.PopulationOfVillagesTownsAndAdministrativeAreas | publisher = Government of Palestine | location = Jerusalem | year = 1932}} \n* {{cite book|last=Morris|first=B.|authorlink=Benny Morris|year=1987|title=The Birth of the Palestinian Refugee Problem|isbn=0-521-33028-9|publisher=Cambridge University Press|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/birthofpalestini00morr}} \n* {{cite book|last=Palmer|first=E.H.|authorlink=Edward Henry Palmer|year=1881|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp00conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Arabic and English Name Lists Collected During the Survey by Lieutenants Conder and Kitchener, R. E. Transliterated and Explained by E.H. Palmer|publisher=[[Palestine Exploration Fund|Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund]]}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Robinson|first1=E.|authorlink1=Edward Robinson (scholar)|last2=Smith|first2=E.|authorlink2=Eli Smith|year=1841|url=https://archive.org/details/biblicalresearch03robiuoft |title=Biblical Researches in Palestine, Mount Sinai and Arabia Petraea: A Journal of Travels in the year 1838|  location=Boston|publisher=[[Crocker & Brewster]]|volume=3}}\n* {{cite book|last=R\u00f6hricht|first=R. |authorlink=Reinhold R\u00f6hricht|title= (RRH) Regesta regni Hierosolymitani (MXCVII-MCCXCI)|url=https://archive.org/details/regestaregnihie00rhgoog|year=1893|publisher=Libraria Academica Wageriana|location=Berlin|language=Latin}}\n* {{cite journal | last = Schumacher | first =G.| authorlink = Gottlieb Schumacher | title = Population list of the Liwa of Akka |  journal = Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund | volume = 20 | pages = 169\u2013191 | url = https://archive.org/details/quarterlystateme19pale | year = 1888}}\n* {{cite book|editor=Strehlke, Ernst |title=Tabulae Ordinis Theutonici ex tabularii regii Berolinensis codice potissimum|url=https://archive.org/details/tabulaeordinist00stregoog|year=1869|publisher=  Weidmanns|location=Berlin}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Tahan |first=Hagit  |date= 2008-12-30   |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=990&mag_id=115   |title=Fassuta Final  Report |publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel|number=121}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.palestineremembered.com/GeoPoints/Fassuta_1132/index.html Welcome To Fassuta]\n* Survey of Western Palestine, Map 4: [http://www.iaa-archives.org.il/zoom/zoom.aspx?folder_id=93&type_id=6&id=8367   IAA], [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Survey_of_Western_Palestine_1880.04.jpg Wikimedia commons]\n{{Northern District (Israel)}}\n\n[[Category:Arab localities in Israel]]\n[[Category:Arab Christian communities in Israel]]\n[[Category:Local councils in Northern District (Israel)]]\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fassuta"}
{"title_page": "BakuBus", "text_new": "[[File:BakuBus. \u015e\u0259rifzad\u0259 k\u00fc\u00e7\u0259si.jpg|thumb|BakuBus]]\n'''BakuBus''' is a company in the capital of [[Azerbaijan]] providing [[Baku]] city with an upgraded bus network. BakuBus LLC was founded on April 3, 2014 to provide passenger transport services in Baku city.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bakubus.az/az|title=About us |website=BakuBus|language=Azerbaijani|access-date=26 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bakubus.az/en|title=About us|website=Bakubus|access-date=26 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Baku Metro]]\n*[[BakuCard]]\n*[[Transport in Azerbaijan]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.bakubus.az/en Official website of BakuBus]\n* [http://www.aeroexpress.az/en Official website of AeroExpress]\n\nOfficial website of [http://www.metro.gov.az/en/ Baku Metropolitan] \n* [http://bna.az/az Official website of Baku Transport Agency]\n\n\n[[Category:Bus transport in Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Transport in Baku]]\n\n{{Azerbaijan-stub}} \n{{Asia-transport-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:BakuBus. \u015e\u0259rifzad\u0259 k\u00fc\u00e7\u0259si.jpg|thumb|BakuBus]]\n'''BakuBus''' is a company in the capital of [[Azerbaijan]] providing [[Baku]] city with an upgraded bus network. BakuBus LLC was founded on April 3, 2014 to provide passenger transport services in Baku city.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bakubus.az/az|title=About us |website=BakuBus|language=Azerbaijani|access-date=26 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bakubus.az/en|title=About us|website=Bakubus|access-date=26 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Baku Metro]]\n*[[BakuCard]]\n*[[Transport in Azerbaijan]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.bakubus.az/en Official website of BakuBus]\n* [http://www.aeroexpress.az/en Official website of AeroExpress]\n\nOfficial website of [http://www.metro.gov.az/en/ Baku Metropolitan] \n* [http://bna.az/az Official website of Baku Transport Agency]\n\n\n[[Category:Bus transport in Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Transport in Baku]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijan stub templates]]\n\n\n{{Asia-transport-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hugo999", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BakuBus"}
{"title_page": "Sanitation worker", "text_new": "{{short description|A person responsible for cleaning and maintaining of a sanitation technology}}\n[[File:Manual pit emptying (8151995298).jpg|thumb|Sanitation workers carrying out manual pit emptying (in Durban, South Africa) with [[personal protective equipment]]]]\nA '''sanitation worker''' is a person responsible for cleaning, maintaining, operating, or emptying the equipment or technology at any step of the [[sanitation]] chain.<ref name=\"worldbank2019\">World Bank, ILO, WaterAid, and WHO (2019). [https://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/3719 Health, Safety and Dignity of Sanitation Workers: An Initial Assessment]. World Bank, Washington, DC.</ref>{{rp|2}} Those workers who maintain and empty on-site sanitation systems (e.g. [[pit latrines]], [[septic tanks]]) contribute to functional [[fecal sludge management]] systems.\n\nSome organisations use the term specifically for [[Waste collector|municipal solid waste collectors]], whereas others exclude the [[Municipal solid waste|solid waste]] (rubbish, trash) sector from its definition.\n\nIt is important to safeguard the dignity, health, and lives of sanitation workers.<ref name=\"GIZ\" />{{rp|19}} Without them, the [[Sustainable Development Goal 6]], Target 6.2 (\"safely managed sanitation for all\") cannot be achieved.<ref name=\"heroes\">Sperandeo, L., Srinivasan, S. (2020). [https://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/3762 The Heroes behind Sanitation - An insight into faecal sludge management workers in Zambia]. BORDA, Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Internationale Zusammenarbeit (GIZ) GmbH, Bonn, Germany</ref>\n\n== Definition ==\n\nA report by [[World Bank]], [[International Labour Organization]], [[WaterAid]] and [[World Health Organization|WHO]] from 2019 defines \"sanitation workers\" to include toilet cleaners and caretakers in domestic, [[Public toilet|public]], and institutional settings; those who empty pits from [[Pit latrine|pit latrines]] and vaults of [[Septic tank|septic tanks]] and other fecal sludge handlers; those who clean sewers and manholes; and those who work at [[Sewage treatment|sewage treatment plants]] and [[Fecal sludge management|fecal sludge treatment]] plants and disposal sites.<ref name=\"worldbank2019\" />{{rp|2}}\n\nIn the United States however, some organisations use the term exclusively for [[Waste collector|municipal solid waste collectors]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.waste360.com/|title=Waste360|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Benelli|first=Natalie|date=2011|title=Sweeping the Streets of the Neoliberal City: Racial and Class Divisions among New York City's Sanitation Workers|url=http://www.portico.org/Portico/article?article=pgk5t03gsr|journal=Journal of Workplace Rights|volume=16|issue=3-4|pages=453\u2013474|doi=10.2190/WR.16.3-4.l|via=}}</ref> A famous example of \"sanitation worker\" referring to waste collectors is the [[Memphis sanitation strike|Memphis Sanitation Workers\u2019 Strike]] in 1968, supported by [[Martin Luther King Jr.]], which brought together both waste collectors and [[sewerage]] maintenance workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.memphislibrary.org/diversity/sanitation-strike-exhibit/sanitation-strike-exhibit-february-11-to-17-edition/memphis-sanitation-workers-strike/|title=MEMPHIS SANITATION WORKERS STRIKE!|last=|first=|date=12 February 1968|website=Memphis Public Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Challenges==\n[[File:Dalberg Water Week Final.webm|thumb|A short video shedding light on the unsafe and undignified working conditions of many sanitation workers in India (2018)]]\n[[File:The tin was lowered into the pit latrine (6975392493).jpg|thumb|Sanitation workers carrying out unsafe manual pit emptying of a [[pit latrine]] in Korogocho slums in Kenya]]\n\nThe challenges faced by sanitation workers can be categorized as follows: [[Occupational safety and health|occupational and environmental health and safety]], legal and institutional issues, financial insecurity, and social issues.<ref name=\"worldbank2019\" />{{rp|7}}\n\nIn many [[Developing country|developing countries]], sanitation workers often have to work with weak legal protection, missing or weak [[Standard operating procedure|standard operating procedures]], weak [[law enforcement]] and few policies protecting their [[Labor rights|rights]] and health.<ref name=\"worldbank2019\" />{{rp|x}}\n\nThe safety of sanitation workers is influenced by:<ref>Eales, K., Blackett, I. (2019). [https://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/3741 FSM5 - Thematic Papers]. Bremen Overseas Research and Development Association (BORDA), Bremen, Germany</ref>{{rp|47}}\n* Design and construction of the toilet or other piece of sanitation infrastructure \n* Pressure by the customer \n* Pressure by the employer \n* Materials and equipment available to do the job\n\nEnvironmental health issues include:\n* diseases related to contact with the excreta <ref>HSE (2011). [https://www.hse.gov.uk/pubns/indg198.pdf Working with sewage\nThe health hazards: A guide for employers], Health and Safety Executive UK. </ref>\n* injuries related to the physical effort of extracting and transporting the waste, including falls from height <ref> [https://www.labour.gov.hk/eng/public/os/D/Manhole.pdf Safety Guide for Work in Manholes] Occupational Safety and Health Branch of the Labour Department, Hong Kong Government</ref>\n* injuries related to cuts from non-feacal waste (e.g. glass or needles) disposed of down the toilet \n* the dangers of working in confined spaces <ref>HSE (2013). [https://www.hse.gov.uk/pubns/indg258.pdf Confined spaces\nA brief guide to working safely], Health and Safety Executive UK.</ref>, including lack of oxygen\n\nOne specific disease that concerns workers in sewers is [[Leptospirosis]], spread through contact with rat urine <ref> HSE (n.d.) [https://www.hse.gov.uk/agriculture/zoonoses-data-sheets/leptospirosis.pdf Leptospirosis (Weil\u2019s Disease and Hardjo)]. Health and Safety Executive UK. </ref>\n\n== Improvements ==\nExamples:\n\n* In Zambia, [[Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Internationale Zusammenarbeit|German Corporation for International Cooperation GmbH]] has been working on projects to \"make sanitation workers more visible and create the recognition and respect that they so rightfully deserve.\"<ref name=\"heroes\" />\n\n== Related occupations or terms ==\nMore generally, a [[waste collector]] (also bin man, garbage collector, etc.) deals with [[municipal solid waste]]. \n\nIn some countries, [[human waste|human excrement]] is still collected from certain types of toilet (such as [[bucket toilet]]s and [[pit latrine]]s) without mechanical equipment and without [[personal protective equipment]]. These workers are \"scooping out feces from \u2018dry\u2019 latrines and overflowing pits\".<ref name=\":2\">Ray, I., Prasad, CS S. (2018). [https://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/3477 Where there are no Sewers - Photoessays on Sanitation Work in Urban India]. Sustainable Sanitation Alliance (SuSanA) secretariat at GIZ, Eschborn, Germany</ref> They are usually working in the [[informal labour]] sector. They are subjected to [[social stigma]] for their work in manually emptying [[septic tanks]] and pit latrines.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/dirty-job-shows-why-cholera-kills-haiti/3654586.html|title=Dirty Job Shows Why Cholera Still Kills in Haiti|date=28 December 2016|work=VOA|access-date=2017-07-30|language=en}}</ref> \n\n===India===\n{{Main|Manual scavenging}}\nIn India the term [[Manual scavenging|manual scavengers]] is used for these workers. The official definition in Indian law is \"manually cleaning, carrying, disposing of, or otherwise handling, human excreta in an insanitary latrine or in an open drain or pit\".<ref name=\":1\">[http://indiacode.nic.in/acts-in-pdf/252013.pdf The Employment Of Manual Scavengers and Construction of Dry Latrines (Prohibition) Act, 1993]. [[Ministry of Housing and Urban Poverty Alleviation (India)|Ministry of Housing and Urban Poverty Alleviation]], Govt. of India.</ref> The practice has officially been banned since 1993 but still continues.\n\n===Haiti===\n{{Main|Bayakou (trade)}}\nIn Haiti, sanitation workers in the informal sector are called ''[[Bayakou (trade)|bayakou]]'', which comes from [[Haitian Creole]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aOichD5n92QC&lpg=PA81&dq=BAYAKOU&pg=PA81#v=onepage&q=BAYAKOU&f=false|title=A Promise in Haiti: A Reporter's Notes on Families and Daily Lives|last=Curnutte|first=Mark|publisher=Vanderbilt University Press|year=2011|isbn=9780826517852|location=Nashville, Tennessee|pages=81}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Rp48dT5eix8C&lpg=PA149&dq=BAYAKOU&pg=PA149#v=onepage&q=BAYAKOU&f=false|title=English Haitian Creole Dictionary|last=Vilsaint|first=F\u00e9qui\u00e8re|last2=Berret|first2=Jean-Evens|publisher=Educa Vision Inc.|year=2005|isbn=9781584322139|edition=2nd|location=Coconut Creek, Florida|pages=149}}</ref> . The capital [[Port-au-Prince]] is one of the largest cities in the world without a [[Sewerage|sewer system]].<ref name=\"haiti\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2013/01/29/150501695/port-au-prince-a-city-of-millions-with-no-sewer-system|title=Port-Au-Prince: A City Of Millions, With No Sewer System|last=Knox|first=Richard|date=13 April 2012|work=NPR|access-date=2017-07-30|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Types of sanitation work ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Types of work and occupations along the sanitation chain (based on <ref name=\"worldbank2019\" />{{rp|3}} but with further additions)\n!Toilet/containment\n!Emptying\n!Conveyance\n!Treatment\n!End use/Disposal\n|-\n|\n* [[Janitor]]\n* [[Restroom attendant]] ([[public toilets]])\n* Sweeping\n* Latrine or [[pit latrine]] cleaning \n* Domestic work ([[domestic worker]])\n* Community/public toilet keeping \n* School toilet cleaning \n* Municipalities, government, and private offices cleaning ([[commercial cleaning]])\n|\n*[[Vacuum truck]] operator\n*Desludging operator<ref>Ramamoorthy, R., Pandey, K. D., Rajakuma, D. S., Ramasamy, N., Sharma, R. (2018). [https://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/3781 Desludging Operators in Tiruchirappalli: An Overview]. Indian Institute for Human Settlements, India</ref>\n*[[Fecal sludge management]] worker<ref name=\"heroes\" />\n*Manual emptying\n* Mechanical emptying (including [[septic tank]] desludging)\n|\n* Manual transport \n* Mechanical transport \n* [[Sewer]] cleaning \n* Sewer and [[pumping station]] maintenance\n* [[Manhole]] cleaning\n|\n* [[Wastewater treatment|Wastewater treatment plant]] operator \n* Sewage treatment plant cleaning\n* Wastewater and sludge handling at sewage treatment plants\n|\n* Manual disposal \n* Mechanical disposal\n|}\n\n== History ==\nIn European history the terms \"[[nightsoil]] collectors\" or \"nightmen\" and [[gong farmer]]<nowiki/>s were used. (The current term for the safe collection of human waste is [[fecal sludge management]].) Towns with sanitation systems based on [[Pail closet|pail closets]] ([[Bucket toilet|bucket toilets]] in [[Outhouse|outhouses]]) relied on frequent emptying, performed by workers driving [[Honeywagon (vehicle)|\"honeywagons\"]], a precursor to the [[vacuum truck]] now used to pump out septage from [[Septic tank|septic tanks]]. The municipal emptying of pail toilets continued in Australia into the second half of the twentieth century; these were known as [[Dunny|dunnies]] and the workers were dunnymen.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sanitationworkers.org/ Sanitation Workers in India]\n\n{{Waste}}\n{{toilets}}\n\n[[Category:Cleaning and maintenance occupations]]\n[[Category:Waste collection| ]]\n[[category:Sanitation]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A person responsible for cleaning and maintaining of a sanitation technology}}\n[[File:Manual pit emptying (8151995298).jpg|thumb|Sanitation workers carrying out manual pit emptying (in Durban, South Africa) with [[personal protective equipment]]]]\nA '''sanitation worker''' is a person responsible for cleaning, maintaining, operating, or emptying the equipment or technology at any step of the [[sanitation]] chain.<ref name=\"worldbank2019\">World Bank, ILO, WaterAid, and WHO (2019). [https://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/3719 Health, Safety and Dignity of Sanitation Workers: An Initial Assessment]. World Bank, Washington, DC.</ref>{{rp|2}} Those workers who maintain and empty on-site sanitation systems (e.g. [[pit latrines]], [[septic tanks]]) contribute to functional [[fecal sludge management]] systems.\n\nSome organisations use the term specifically for [[Waste collector|municipal solid waste collectors]], whereas others exclude the [[Municipal solid waste|solid waste]] (rubbish, trash) sector from its definition.\n\nIt is important to safeguard the dignity, health, and lives of sanitation workers.<ref name=\"GIZ\" />{{rp|19}} Without them, the [[Sustainable Development Goal 6]], Target 6.2 (\"safely managed sanitation for all\") cannot be achieved.<ref name=\"heroes\">Sperandeo, L., Srinivasan, S. (2020). [https://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/3762 The Heroes behind Sanitation - An insight into faecal sludge management workers in Zambia]. BORDA, Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Internationale Zusammenarbeit (GIZ) GmbH, Bonn, Germany</ref>\n\n== Definition ==\n\nA report by [[World Bank]], [[International Labour Organization]], [[WaterAid]] and [[World Health Organization|WHO]] from 2019 defines \"sanitation workers\" to include toilet cleaners and caretakers in domestic, [[Public toilet|public]], and institutional settings; those who empty pits from [[Pit latrine|pit latrines]] and vaults of [[Septic tank|septic tanks]] and other fecal sludge handlers; those who clean sewers and manholes; and those who work at [[Sewage treatment|sewage treatment plants]] and [[Fecal sludge management|fecal sludge treatment]] plants and disposal sites.<ref name=\"worldbank2019\" />{{rp|2}}\n\nIn the United States however, some organisations use the term exclusively for [[Waste collector|municipal solid waste collectors]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.waste360.com/|title=Waste360|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Benelli|first=Natalie|date=2011|title=Sweeping the Streets of the Neoliberal City: Racial and Class Divisions among New York City's Sanitation Workers|url=http://www.portico.org/Portico/article?article=pgk5t03gsr|journal=Journal of Workplace Rights|volume=16|issue=3-4|pages=453\u2013474|doi=10.2190/WR.16.3-4.l|via=}}</ref> A famous example of \"sanitation worker\" referring to waste collectors is the [[Memphis sanitation strike|Memphis Sanitation Workers\u2019 Strike]] in 1968, supported by [[Martin Luther King Jr.]], which brought together both waste collectors and [[sewerage]] maintenance workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.memphislibrary.org/diversity/sanitation-strike-exhibit/sanitation-strike-exhibit-february-11-to-17-edition/memphis-sanitation-workers-strike/|title=MEMPHIS SANITATION WORKERS STRIKE!|last=|first=|date=12 February 1968|website=Memphis Public Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Challenges==\n[[File:Dalberg Water Week Final.webm|thumb|A short video shedding light on the unsafe and undignified working conditions of many sanitation workers in India (2018)]]\n[[File:The tin was lowered into the pit latrine (6975392493).jpg|thumb|Sanitation workers carrying out unsafe manual pit emptying of a [[pit latrine]] in Korogocho slums in Kenya]]\n\nThe challenges faced by sanitation workers can be categorized as follows: [[Occupational safety and health|occupational and environmental health and safety]], legal and institutional issues, financial insecurity, and social issues.<ref name=\"worldbank2019\" />{{rp|7}}\n\nIn many [[Developing country|developing countries]], sanitation workers often have to work with weak legal protection, missing or weak [[Standard operating procedure|standard operating procedures]], weak [[law enforcement]] and few policies protecting their [[Labor rights|rights]] and health.<ref name=\"worldbank2019\" />{{rp|x}}\n\nThe safety of sanitation workers is influenced by:<ref>Eales, K., Blackett, I. (2019). [https://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/3741 FSM5 - Thematic Papers]. Bremen Overseas Research and Development Association (BORDA), Bremen, Germany</ref>{{rp|47}}\n* Design and construction of the toilet or other piece of sanitation infrastructure \n* Pressure by the customer \n* Pressure by the employer \n* Materials and equipment available to do the job\n\nEnvironmental health issues include:\n* diseases related to contact with the excreta <ref>HSE (2011). [https://www.hse.gov.uk/pubns/indg198.pdf Working with sewage\nThe health hazards: A guide for employers], Health and Safety Executive UK. </ref>\n* injuries related to the physical effort of extracting and transporting the waste, including falls from height\n* injuries related to cuts from non-feacal waste (e.g. glass or needles) disposed of down the toilet \n* the dangers of working in confined spaces <ref>HSE (2013). [https://www.hse.gov.uk/pubns/indg258.pdf Confined spaces\nA brief guide to working safely], Health and Safety Executive UK.</ref>, including lack of oxygen\n\nOne specific disease that concerns workers in sewers is [[Leptospirosis]], spread through contact with rat urine <ref> HSE (n.d.) [https://www.hse.gov.uk/agriculture/zoonoses-data-sheets/leptospirosis.pdf Leptospirosis (Weil\u2019s Disease and Hardjo)]. Health and Safety Executive UK. </ref>\n\n== Improvements ==\nExamples:\n\n* In Zambia, [[Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Internationale Zusammenarbeit|German Corporation for International Cooperation GmbH]] has been working on projects to \"make sanitation workers more visible and create the recognition and respect that they so rightfully deserve.\"<ref name=\"heroes\" />\n\n== Related occupations or terms ==\nMore generally, a [[waste collector]] (also bin man, garbage collector, etc.) deals with [[municipal solid waste]]. \n\nIn some countries, [[human waste|human excrement]] is still collected from certain types of toilet (such as [[bucket toilet]]s and [[pit latrine]]s) without mechanical equipment and without [[personal protective equipment]]. These workers are \"scooping out feces from \u2018dry\u2019 latrines and overflowing pits\".<ref name=\":2\">Ray, I., Prasad, CS S. (2018). [https://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/3477 Where there are no Sewers - Photoessays on Sanitation Work in Urban India]. Sustainable Sanitation Alliance (SuSanA) secretariat at GIZ, Eschborn, Germany</ref> They are usually working in the [[informal labour]] sector. They are subjected to [[social stigma]] for their work in manually emptying [[septic tanks]] and pit latrines.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/dirty-job-shows-why-cholera-kills-haiti/3654586.html|title=Dirty Job Shows Why Cholera Still Kills in Haiti|date=28 December 2016|work=VOA|access-date=2017-07-30|language=en}}</ref> \n\n===India===\n{{Main|Manual scavenging}}\nIn India the term [[Manual scavenging|manual scavengers]] is used for these workers. The official definition in Indian law is \"manually cleaning, carrying, disposing of, or otherwise handling, human excreta in an insanitary latrine or in an open drain or pit\".<ref name=\":1\">[http://indiacode.nic.in/acts-in-pdf/252013.pdf The Employment Of Manual Scavengers and Construction of Dry Latrines (Prohibition) Act, 1993]. [[Ministry of Housing and Urban Poverty Alleviation (India)|Ministry of Housing and Urban Poverty Alleviation]], Govt. of India.</ref> The practice has officially been banned since 1993 but still continues.\n\n===Haiti===\n{{Main|Bayakou (trade)}}\nIn Haiti, sanitation workers in the informal sector are called ''[[Bayakou (trade)|bayakou]]'', which comes from [[Haitian Creole]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aOichD5n92QC&lpg=PA81&dq=BAYAKOU&pg=PA81#v=onepage&q=BAYAKOU&f=false|title=A Promise in Haiti: A Reporter's Notes on Families and Daily Lives|last=Curnutte|first=Mark|publisher=Vanderbilt University Press|year=2011|isbn=9780826517852|location=Nashville, Tennessee|pages=81}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Rp48dT5eix8C&lpg=PA149&dq=BAYAKOU&pg=PA149#v=onepage&q=BAYAKOU&f=false|title=English Haitian Creole Dictionary|last=Vilsaint|first=F\u00e9qui\u00e8re|last2=Berret|first2=Jean-Evens|publisher=Educa Vision Inc.|year=2005|isbn=9781584322139|edition=2nd|location=Coconut Creek, Florida|pages=149}}</ref> . The capital [[Port-au-Prince]] is one of the largest cities in the world without a [[Sewerage|sewer system]].<ref name=\"haiti\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2013/01/29/150501695/port-au-prince-a-city-of-millions-with-no-sewer-system|title=Port-Au-Prince: A City Of Millions, With No Sewer System|last=Knox|first=Richard|date=13 April 2012|work=NPR|access-date=2017-07-30|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Types of sanitation work ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Types of work and occupations along the sanitation chain (based on <ref name=\"worldbank2019\" />{{rp|3}} but with further additions)\n!Toilet/containment\n!Emptying\n!Conveyance\n!Treatment\n!End use/Disposal\n|-\n|\n* [[Janitor]]\n* [[Restroom attendant]] ([[public toilets]])\n* Sweeping\n* Latrine or [[pit latrine]] cleaning \n* Domestic work ([[domestic worker]])\n* Community/public toilet keeping \n* School toilet cleaning \n* Municipalities, government, and private offices cleaning ([[commercial cleaning]])\n|\n*[[Vacuum truck]] operator\n*Desludging operator<ref>Ramamoorthy, R., Pandey, K. D., Rajakuma, D. S., Ramasamy, N., Sharma, R. (2018). [https://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/3781 Desludging Operators in Tiruchirappalli: An Overview]. Indian Institute for Human Settlements, India</ref>\n*[[Fecal sludge management]] worker<ref name=\"heroes\" />\n*Manual emptying\n* Mechanical emptying (including [[septic tank]] desludging)\n|\n* Manual transport \n* Mechanical transport \n* [[Sewer]] cleaning \n* Sewer and [[pumping station]] maintenance\n* [[Manhole]] cleaning\n|\n* [[Wastewater treatment|Wastewater treatment plant]] operator \n* Sewage treatment plant cleaning\n* Wastewater and sludge handling at sewage treatment plants\n|\n* Manual disposal \n* Mechanical disposal\n|}\n\n== History ==\nIn European history the terms \"[[nightsoil]] collectors\" or \"nightmen\" and [[gong farmer]]<nowiki/>s were used. (The current term for the safe collection of human waste is [[fecal sludge management]].) Towns with sanitation systems based on [[Pail closet|pail closets]] ([[Bucket toilet|bucket toilets]] in [[Outhouse|outhouses]]) relied on frequent emptying, performed by workers driving [[Honeywagon (vehicle)|\"honeywagons\"]], a precursor to the [[vacuum truck]] now used to pump out septage from [[Septic tank|septic tanks]]. The municipal emptying of pail toilets continued in Australia into the second half of the twentieth century; these were known as [[Dunny|dunnies]] and the workers were dunnymen.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sanitationworkers.org/ Sanitation Workers in India]\n\n{{Waste